[[File:KinKannonji Nisshudo.JPG|thumb|256px|Stalactite Cave “Nichishū-dō”]]
'''Kinmu Kannon-ji''' (金武観音寺, きんかんのんじ) is a temple of the {{ill|Koyasan Shingon Sect|ja|高野山真言宗}} located in {{ill|Okinawa Prefecture|ja|沖縄県}}, {{ill|Kunigami District|ja|国頭郡}}, {{ill|Kin Town|ja|金武町}}. Its mountain name is {{ill|Kinmōzan|ja|金峯山}}, and its principal image is {{ill|Holy Kannon|ja|聖観音}}. In Okinawa—where many temple and shrine structures were lost during the {{ill|Pacific War|ja|太平洋戦争}}—this temple is a rare surviving example of prewar traditional wooden architecture.

== History ==
According to tradition, the temple was founded in the 16th century by {{ill|Nichishū Shōnin|ja|日秀上人}}. In the early 16th century, it is said that Nichishū Shōnin set out from {{ill|Kii Province|ja|紀伊国}} to head for {{ill|China|ja|唐}} (one theory holds that he sought the Western Pure Land by means of the {{ill|Hotarakuto Kai|ja|補陀落渡海}}), but was shipwrecked and drifted to the port of Funaya (also known as Fukahaka Port) in Kin within the {{ill|Ryukyu Kingdom|ja|琉球王国}}. Thereafter, he based his missionary activities in a stalactite cave in Kin, around which he established the temple. This cave is known as {{ill|Nichishū-dō|ja|日秀洞}}. The present building, which was rebuilt in 1942 (Showa 17) following a fire in 1934 (Showa 9), remains standing.

== Other ==
* In 1984 (Showa 59) on June 1, the main hall was designated as a cultural property by Kin Town.
* In 1991 (Heisei 3) on December 24, the fukugi trees within the temple grounds were designated as cultural property by Kin Town.

